content.text: JavaScript Object.defineProperty()

content.text: Adding a new Property
This example adds a new property to an object:
content.html: This example adds a new property to an object:

content.code_html:
// Create an Object:
const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName : "Doe",
  language : "EN"
};

// Add a Property
Object.defineProperty(person, "year", {value:"2008"});

content.text: Changing a Property Value
This example changes a property value:
content.html: This example changes a property value:

content.code_html:
// Create an Object:
 const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName : "Doe",
  language : "EN"
};

// Change a Property
Object.defineProperty(person, "language", {value : "NO"});

content.text: Property Attributes
All properties have a name. In addition they also have a value.
content.html: All properties have a name. In addition they also have a value.

content.text: The value is one of the property's attributes.
content.html: The value is one of the property's attributes.

content.text: Other attributes are: enumerable, configurable, and writable.
content.html: Other attributes are: enumerable, configurable, and writable.

content.text: These attributes define how the property can be accessed (is it readable?, is it writable?)
content.html: These attributes define how the property can be accessed (is it readable?, is it writable?)

content.text: In JavaScript, all attributes can be read, but only the value attribute can be changed (and only if the property is writable).
content.html: In JavaScript, all attributes can be read, but only the value attribute can be changed (and only if the property is writable).

content.text: ( ECMAScript 5 has methods for both getting and setting all property attributes)
content.html: ( ECMAScript 5 has methods for both getting and setting all property attributes)

content.text: JavaScript getOwnPropertyNames()
The Object.getOwnPropertyNames() method can:
content.html: The Object.getOwnPropertyNames() method can:

content.text: Syntax
List all Object Properties
This example gets all properties of an object:
content.html: This example gets all properties of an object:

content.code_html:
// Create an Object
 const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName : "Doe",
  language : "EN"
};

// Get all Properties
 Object.getOwnPropertyNames(person);

content.text: Object.getOwnPropertyNames() will also list properties that is not enumerable:
content.html: Object.getOwnPropertyNames() will also list properties that is not enumerable:

  firstName: "John",
  lastName : "Doe",
  language : "EN"
};

// Set the language Property not enumerable
 Object.defineProperty(person, "language", {enumerable:false});

// Get all Properties
 Object.getOwnPropertyNames(person);

content.text: JavaScript Object.keys()
The Object.keys() method can:
content.html: The Object.keys() method can:

content.text: Syntax
List Enumerable Object Properties
This example uses Object.keys() insted of Object.getOwnPropertyNames() :
content.html: This example uses Object.keys() insted of Object.getOwnPropertyNames():

content.code_html:
// Create an Object
 const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName : "Doe",
  language : "EN"
};

// Change the "language" Property
 Object.defineProperty(person, "language", {enumerable:false});

// Get all Enumerable Properties
 Object.keys(person);

content.text: Note
The getOwnPropertyNames() method returns all properties.
content.html: The getOwnPropertyNames() method returns all properties.

content.text: The Object.keys() method returns all enumerable properties.
content.html: The Object.keys() method returns all enumerable properties.

content.text: If you define object properties without enumerable:false , the two methods will return the same.
content.html: If you define object properties without enumerable:false, the two methods will return the same.

content.text: Adding Getters and Setters
The Object.defineProperty() method can also be used to add Getters and Setters:
content.html: The Object.defineProperty() method can also be used to add Getters and Setters:

content.code_html:
//Create an object
const person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe"};

// Define a getter
Object.defineProperty(person, "fullName", {
  get: function () {return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;}
});

content.text: A Counter Example

content.code_html:
// Define object
 const obj = {counter:0};

// Define setters
 Object.defineProperty(obj, "reset", {
  get : function () {this.counter = 0;}
});
Object.defineProperty(obj, "increment", {
  get : function () {this.counter++;}
});
Object.defineProperty(obj, "decrement", {
  get : function () {this.counter--;}
});
Object.defineProperty(obj, "add", {
  set : function (value) {this.counter += value;}
});
Object.defineProperty(obj, "subtract", {
  set : function (i) {this.counter -= i;}
});

// Play with the counter:
 obj.reset;
obj.add = 5;
obj.subtract = 1;
obj.increment;
obj.decrement;

content.text: Prototype Properties
JavaScript objects inherit the properties of their prototype.
content.html: JavaScript objects inherit the properties of their prototype.

content.text: The delete keyword does not delete inherited properties, but if you delete a prototype property, it will affect all objects inherited from the prototype.
content.html: The delete keyword does not delete inherited properties, but if you delete a prototype property, it will affect all objects inherited from the prototype.
